-- в”Ђв”Ђ Kestra в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source, event-driven orchestration platform that lets teams build data, AI and infrastructure workflows with YAML and 1,200+ plugins.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$51-200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Kestra Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Kestra review covering features, pricing tiers, plugins and how it compares to Airflow, Prefect and Dagster for workflow orchestration.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Kestra is an open-source, event-driven orchestration platform founded in 2021 in Paris, France by Emmanuel Darras, a co-founder of the gaming studio Ankama, together with CTO Ludovic Dehon. The company, formally Kestra Technologies, has raised roughly 31 million euros (about 36 million dollars) in total funding, including a 3 million dollar pre-seed round in 2023, an 8 million dollar seed round in September 2024, and a 21 million euro (about 25 million dollar) Series A led by RTP Global with participation from Alven, ISAI and Axeleo, announced in March 2026. Kestra reports serving around 30,000 organizations globally and executing more than 2 billion workflow runs in 2025, a twentyfold increase year over year, with enterprise users reportedly including Apple, Toyota, JPMorgan Chase, BHP, Bloomberg, Credit Agricole and Xiaomi. Architecturally, Kestra is a declarative, YAML-based orchestration engine that treats workflows as code while also offering a visual, UI-based flow builder, positioning itself as a polyglot alternative to Python-only tools such as Apache Airflow and Prefect. It supports both scheduled and event-driven triggers, meaning flows can react to webhooks, message queues, file arrivals or API calls rather than only running on a cron schedule. The platform ships with more than 1,200 plugins covering databases, cloud providers (AWS, GCP, Azure), data warehouses, dbt, Python, container and Kubernetes execution, AI and LLM tasks, and general-purpose scripting in nearly any language, letting a single flow orchestrate tasks written in different languages and runtimes. Kestra can be self-hosted for free as fully open-source software with unlimited flows and executions, deployed on-premises, in a private cloud, or in air-gapped environments. Kestra Cloud is the company's fully managed SaaS offering, billed on a pay-as-you-consume usage basis, and includes automatic scaling, built-in security and governance, enterprise plugins, and SOC2 compliance without the customer needing to operate infrastructure. The Enterprise Edition is a self-managed or private-cloud deployment sold under an annual per-instance subscription with custom, quote-based pricing that scales with organization size and required features; it layers on LDAP, SCIM and custom role-based access control, single sign-on and public-cloud authentication integrations, audit logs, storage isolation, multi-tenancy, worker groups and dedicated task runners, external secret manager integrations, enterprise-exclusive plugins, an AI Copilot with support for custom models, and a customer success program with SLA-backed support (Standard by default, with Premium and Platinum tiers available). Kestra targets data engineering, platform engineering and DevOps teams inside mid-market and large enterprises who need to orchestrate ETL/ELT pipelines, machine learning workflows, business process automation, and infrastructure tasks across heterogeneous tech stacks without being locked into a single programming language. Its most direct competitors are Apache Airflow, whose Python-DAG-first model is mature but can be harder to version and roll back and is less friendly to non-Python teams; Prefect, which offers a strong Python developer experience via decorators but is fundamentally Python-only; Dagster, which takes an asset-centric approach optimized for data lineage, testability and dbt-heavy pipelines rather than general task orchestration; and Astronomer, a managed-Airflow vendor. Kestra differentiates itself by combining a declarative, language-agnostic workflow definition format with native event-driven triggering, a large first-party plugin catalog, and a tiered path from free self-hosted open source through managed cloud to enterprise governance features, aiming to reduce the operational complexity that comes with running and scaling traditional orchestrators like Airflow at enterprise volume.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '4ba1dde9-3a3c-4472-af05-215a5ccd715d';

