-- в”Ђв”Ђ KeyDB в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source, multi-threaded fork of Redis built for higher throughput and lower latency while staying protocol-compatible with Redis.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Santa Monica, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$KeyDB Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$KeyDB review covering multi-threading, performance benchmarks, Redis compatibility, and how it compares to Redis, Valkey and Dragonfly.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$KeyDB is an open-source, high-performance fork of Redis originally created by John Sully and Ben Schermel at EQ Alpha Technology, and later acquired by Snap Inc. (the parent company of Snapchat) in May 2022, after Snap had already been running KeyDB across a significant portion of its own caching infrastructure. As part of the acquisition, Snap brought the formerly commercial 'KeyDB Pro' features into the open-source codebase and relicensed the project under BSD-3, making the full feature set freely available; the KeyDB team and repository are now maintained as part of Snap Inc., with the project hosted at github.com/Snapchat/KeyDB. KeyDB's central architectural differentiation from standard Redis is multi-threading: where Redis runs a single-threaded event loop for command processing, KeyDB runs the same event loop concurrently across multiple threads, assigning each client connection to a thread on accept() while guarding access to the core hash table with a spinlock, and implements a multi-version concurrency control (MVCC) layer that lets it serve consistent point-in-time snapshots of the dataset without blocking on operations like SCAN or KEYS the way single-threaded Redis can. This design lets a single KeyDB node benchmark over one million operations per second and deliver substantially higher throughput on multi-core hardware, including up to roughly seven times the throughput of Redis when TLS encryption is enabled, since TLS handshake and encryption overhead can also be parallelized across threads. KeyDB maintains full wire-protocol compatibility with Redis, including support for Redis modules and Lua scripts, and supports the same core data structures Redis offers (strings, hashes, lists, sets, sorted sets, bitmaps, HyperLogLogs, geospatial indexes and streams), positioning itself as a drop-in replacement that requires no client-side code changes for teams migrating from Redis. Beyond raw threading, KeyDB adds features not present in vanilla open-source Redis, including Active Replication (also called multi-master or active-active replication, allowing multiple KeyDB nodes to accept writes and replicate to each other without requiring separate Sentinel nodes for failover), Subkey Expires (allowing individual members within complex data structures like hashes to have their own TTL rather than only whole-key expiration), and ModJS, a JavaScript-based module system built on the V8 engine intended as a faster alternative to Lua for custom scripting. KeyDB also supports cluster-mode sharding for horizontal scale-out with automatic failover, and persistence options comparable to Redis, including periodic RDB-style snapshotting and append-only-file (AOF) command logging, with configurable durability trade-offs. The project has continued to develop additional capabilities such as FLASH-tiered storage (extending the effective in-memory dataset to disk/flash for larger-than-RAM workloads) and multi-tenancy features. Because KeyDB is fully open-source with no separate paid tier, licensing, or subscription, it is used by engineering teams as a free, self-hosted, drop-in Redis alternative for caching, session storage, pub/sub messaging, real-time leaderboards, and other in-memory data use cases where higher per-node throughput on multi-core machines is valuable, without the cost or lock-in of a managed database service. Its primary competitors are Redis itself (including Redis Inc.'s post-2024 relicensed 'Redis' and Redis Enterprise offerings), Valkey (the Linux Foundation-backed, community-governed fork of Redis created after Redis's license change, to which Snap itself migrated its own caching infrastructure roughly two years after acquiring KeyDB), and Dragonfly, another multi-threaded, drop-in Redis-compatible in-memory database built from scratch for modern multi-core hardware. KeyDB differentiates itself from Redis primarily through multi-threaded performance and features like active replication and subkey expiration at zero licensing cost, though its long-term project momentum has been questioned somewhat by the fact that even its own corporate steward, Snap, subsequently moved its production caching workloads to Valkey, the more broadly community-governed fork.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5090858f-f936-401a-988e-90e50e3c63af';

